

# 50-character subject line:
#
# <type>[optional scope]: <description>
#
# 72-character wrapped longer description. This should answer:
#
# * Why was this change necessary?
# * How does it address the problem?
# * Are there any side effects?
#
# Include a link to the ticket, if any.
#
# Add co-authors if you worked on this code with others:
#
# Co-authored-by: Full Name <email@example.com>
# Co-authored-by: Full Name <email@example.com>
#
# Other "Conventional Commits" footer(s).
#
# Here is a regular expression to validate message widths:
# \S.{0,49}((\r\n|\r|\n)(\r\n|\r|\n).{1,72}((\r\n|\r|\n){1,2}.{1,72}(\r\n|\r|\n)?)*)*
#
# Interesting reads:
# Tim Pope: https://tbaggery.com/2008/04/19/a-note-about-git-commit-messages.html
# Toughtbot: https://thoughtbot.com/blog/5-useful-tips-for-a-better-commit-message
# Commit message style guide for Git: https://commit.style/
# Conventional Commits: https://www.conventionalcommits.org
#
# Conventional Commits types:
# - fix: a bug fix
# - feat: a new feature
# - build: changes that affect the build system or external dependencies
# - chore: tool changes, configuration changes, and other things that do not go into production
# - ci: changes to CI configuration files and scripts
# - docs: documentation *only* changes
# - style: changes that do not affect the meaning of the code (white-space, formatting, missing semi-colons, etc)
# - refactor: a code change that neither fixes a bug nor adds a feature
# - test: adding missing tests or correcting existing tests
# - perf: for performance improvements
#
# Inspired by:
# - https://github.com/conventional-changelog/commitlint/tree/master/%40commitlint/config-conventional
# - https://github.com/angular/angular/blob/22b96b9/CONTRIBUTING.md#-commit-message-guidelines
# - http://karma-runner.github.io/6.3/dev/git-commit-msg.html
